00:11:48.700 --> 00:11:55.340
So in quite a few Hangouts, we've talked a bit around like data stewardship and data

00:11:55.340 --> 00:11:58.099
governance and what those words mean.

00:11:58.099 --> 00:12:03.539
And so we actually have a roundtable conversation with the community next week on data stewardship

00:12:03.539 --> 00:12:05.500
at the individual level.

00:12:05.500 --> 00:12:09.380
And I was just wondering to hear from you, like, how do you distinguish between data

00:12:09.380 --> 00:12:16.700
stewardship and data governance or what, or how would you explain data governance?

00:12:17.700 --> 00:12:18.700
Okay.

00:12:18.700 --> 00:12:26.500
Let me just think for a second.

00:12:26.500 --> 00:12:33.340
And I'll share that event in the chat here, too, if anybody wants to join this conversation

00:12:33.340 --> 00:12:35.539
next week, too.

00:12:35.539 --> 00:12:45.900
I mean, my initial thought is, I think governance is more of a security kind of a thing, ensuring

00:12:46.099 --> 00:12:49.979
that people have, the right people have access to the right data.

00:12:49.979 --> 00:12:52.619
And it's for a few different reasons.

00:12:52.619 --> 00:12:58.859
It could be, it's a risk to the company to let certain data come out.

00:12:58.859 --> 00:13:01.780
I mean, that's like financial data, it could be like that.

00:13:01.780 --> 00:13:06.659
But also it could be that there's compliance risks, and that would be things like personally

00:13:06.659 --> 00:13:08.739
identifiable information.

00:13:08.739 --> 00:13:14.179
So governance is like ensuring that you don't leak any of that and that you're fully compliant

00:13:14.340 --> 00:13:17.820
with, and you're avoiding risks, I would say.

00:13:17.820 --> 00:13:21.299
Stewardship to me, I actually don't have like a great definition for that, but what it sounds

00:13:21.299 --> 00:13:25.419
like to me is something more on the individual level.

00:13:25.419 --> 00:13:31.900
So like if I'm tasked with a project, right, like I have a certain use case that I've been

00:13:31.900 --> 00:13:33.900
asked to build out.

00:13:33.900 --> 00:13:38.500
And usually in my experience with the way this starts is like, okay, here's some tables

00:13:38.500 --> 00:13:42.859
in the data lake or the data warehouse or whatever, this is where you can go find the

00:13:42.859 --> 00:13:45.739
data and like you get started with that.

00:13:45.739 --> 00:13:50.739
Inevitably, you're going to wind up creating some sort of derivative datasets from there.

00:13:50.739 --> 00:13:54.059
And I think being a good, some of the question becomes like, are you going to be a good steward

00:13:54.059 --> 00:13:56.700
of that data or not?

00:13:56.700 --> 00:13:58.900
So what does it mean to be a good steward of that data?

00:13:58.900 --> 00:14:03.820
So to me, that would mean, are you clearly documenting everything associated with that?

00:14:03.820 --> 00:14:11.059
Are you documenting the code that you wrote to transform it into the derived datasets?

00:14:11.059 --> 00:14:15.140
Are you documenting the datasets themselves?

00:14:15.140 --> 00:14:19.099
Databricks has pretty good support for these kinds of things, but if nothing else, like

00:14:19.099 --> 00:14:23.979
make a page in Confluence or a Google doc or a Word doc, whatever it is, where you actually

00:14:23.979 --> 00:14:28.739
describe like, okay, this derivative table came from these other tables.

00:14:28.739 --> 00:14:30.700
This is what these columns mean.

00:14:30.700 --> 00:14:34.619
And it's somewhere that people can actually find it and understand it.

00:14:34.619 --> 00:14:38.380
That to me would be data stewardship.

00:14:38.380 --> 00:14:43.739
And obviously being a poor data steward would be like not commenting your code, not commenting

00:14:43.739 --> 00:14:47.979
any of your tables and having hard to read obscure column names.

00:14:47.979 --> 00:14:51.219
And then when somebody finds your data, it could be the most valuable data in the world

00:14:51.219 --> 00:14:55.539
for your organization, but it's just like, who's going to know what that means?

00:14:55.539 --> 00:14:59.580
So I think that's like the distinction between governance, which is more risk and security

00:14:59.580 --> 00:15:03.580
oriented and stewardship, which is more maybe closer to like data quality or something like

00:15:03.580 --> 00:15:04.580
that.

00:15:04.580 --> 00:15:05.580
Thank you.

00:15:05.780 --> 00:15:06.780
Thank you.

