So let's say the three main open source technologies from Databricks today are Apache

00:17:15.979 --> 00:17:18.979
Spark, Delta Lake, and MLflow.

00:17:18.979 --> 00:17:22.979
Apache Spark is an engine.

00:17:22.979 --> 00:17:24.979
It's a computing engine.

00:17:24.979 --> 00:17:26.979
It's a big data computing engine.

00:17:27.579 --> 00:17:33.579
MLflow is a storage format slash table format.

00:17:33.579 --> 00:17:39.579
And MLflow is a framework for managing machine learning models throughout their entire

00:17:39.579 --> 00:17:41.579
lifecycle.

00:17:41.579 --> 00:17:47.579
So if you want to learn about these, all three of them have their own open source, like

00:17:47.579 --> 00:17:49.579
websites for the open source project.

00:17:49.579 --> 00:17:51.579
And there's tutorials there.

00:17:51.579 --> 00:17:55.579
There's instructions on how to download it anywhere, install it on whatever computer, your

00:17:56.180 --> 00:18:04.180
And you can totally do the hello world examples and maybe even go beyond that and do a few

00:18:04.180 --> 00:18:06.180
levels beyond that.

00:18:06.180 --> 00:18:14.180
And of course, now there's like tons of videos on the Internet to explain all these things.

00:18:14.180 --> 00:18:18.180
But if you want to go to production, I think that that becomes a different story.

00:18:18.180 --> 00:18:24.180
Because then when there's production, when you want to have an application or some use

00:18:24.780 --> 00:18:28.780
of production, you have to start thinking about the risk of it failing.

00:18:28.780 --> 00:18:32.780
If it's something that's on your laptop that's personal, probably not that much risk of it

00:18:32.780 --> 00:18:34.780
failing.

00:18:34.780 --> 00:18:36.780
If it's a business case that's been decided on the business, we're going to invest, we're

00:18:36.780 --> 00:18:40.780
going to put all of our people on this and we're going to build this out.

00:18:40.780 --> 00:18:42.780
That's a lot of risk immediately.

00:18:42.780 --> 00:18:48.780
So for that, you have to start thinking about more DevOps and like engineering type concepts

00:18:49.380 --> 00:18:53.380
How do I ensure that this is actually going to scale and that it's reliable?

00:18:53.380 --> 00:18:57.380
Whatever system that we're installing all this software onto and we're actually managing

00:18:57.380 --> 00:18:59.380
it.

00:18:59.380 --> 00:19:03.380
You have to think of who is going to manage the infrastructure that this is running on.

00:19:03.380 --> 00:19:09.380
And you also have to think about like how are we, let's say we get this up and running

00:19:09.380 --> 00:19:13.380
and inevitably we'll have to make some sort of changes to it.

00:19:13.380 --> 00:19:17.380
How are we going to make sure that when we make changes that we don't break anything?

00:19:17.979 --> 00:19:19.979
These are all much bigger problems.

00:19:19.979 --> 00:19:21.979
How do we make it secure?

00:19:21.979 --> 00:19:25.979
These are all the things that I've seen over the past, all the years that I've been in

00:19:25.979 --> 00:19:27.979
field engineering.

00:19:27.979 --> 00:19:33.979
There's this tension between DIY because you look at open source, you're like, oh, it's

00:19:33.979 --> 00:19:35.979
cheaper if we just do it ourselves.

00:19:35.979 --> 00:19:39.979
Versus a managed service where the managed service takes care of a lot of those things

00:19:39.979 --> 00:19:41.979
for you.

00:19:41.979 --> 00:19:45.979
The managed service will say, I guarantee that the infrastructure will be reliable.

00:19:46.579 --> 00:19:48.579
I guarantee that it will be secure.

00:19:48.579 --> 00:19:50.579
So you don't have to spend any money on that.

00:19:50.579 --> 00:19:54.579
You just pay me some and I'll make sure that the environment is totally secure and

00:19:54.579 --> 00:19:56.579
reliable.

00:19:56.579 --> 00:20:04.579
So I think that that's kind of the, that's like the tradeoff that you have to think about

00:20:04.579 --> 00:20:08.579
when you think about I have this interesting technology, this useful technology.

00:20:08.579 --> 00:20:10.579
How do I get this into production?

00:20:11.180 --> 00:20:17.180
You have to think about the tradeoff between spending money on people to manage it at your

00:20:17.180 --> 00:20:21.180
company or paying for a managed service.

00:20:21.180 --> 00:20:27.180
I think in many cases, depending upon what the managed service is, it could be worth

00:20:27.180 --> 00:20:29.180
it or it could be worth it to DIY.

00:20:29.180 --> 00:20:37.180
But that's certainly, I hear a lot of customers like lean, customers that lean towards the

00:20:37.780 --> 00:20:39.780
managed service approach.

00:20:39.780 --> 00:20:45.780
I find that they're not always thinking about the total cost of ownership and like what

00:20:45.780 --> 00:20:49.780
the full-time employees that have to maintain the infrastructure are pretty expensive.

00:20:49.780 --> 00:20:53.780
So that's kind of my perspective on it.

00:20:53.780 --> 00:20:57.780
Working with customers at a managed service company for five years.

