00:45:01.780 --> 00:45:09.780
So this question, this has been asked to me a lot of times about how do I

00:45:09.780 --> 00:45:17.780
validate my data in a project or how do I constantly do integrity checks

00:45:17.780 --> 00:45:23.780
or check for integrity issues in my project?

00:45:23.780 --> 00:45:25.780
So how should I answer that?

00:45:25.780 --> 00:45:29.780
Or what should be my answer to that?

00:45:29.780 --> 00:45:31.780
Yep.

00:45:31.780 --> 00:45:33.780
Important question.

00:45:34.780 --> 00:45:41.780
The, so what I think data validation means to me, as I understand it,

00:45:41.780 --> 00:45:45.780
is you can't just necessarily rely on anything that you get coming in

00:45:45.780 --> 00:45:48.780
from some source system, right?

00:45:48.780 --> 00:45:51.780
You have to check and make sure that the data actually makes sense.

00:45:51.780 --> 00:45:56.780
So for example, let's say that you have a date.

00:45:56.780 --> 00:45:58.780
This is a classic example.

00:45:58.780 --> 00:46:03.780
Let's say you have a date for a sale for some product from your company

00:46:03.780 --> 00:46:07.780
and your company started in 2015.

00:46:07.780 --> 00:46:13.780
You have a record come in that the date of the product sold is like 1970

00:46:13.780 --> 00:46:15.780
or 1990 or something like that, right?

00:46:15.780 --> 00:46:16.780
So it's impossible.

00:46:16.780 --> 00:46:17.780
It makes no sense.

00:46:17.780 --> 00:46:21.780
So validating the data means did you check to make sure that all of this

00:46:21.780 --> 00:46:26.780
is actually correct and sane?

00:46:26.780 --> 00:46:28.780
That's what I think data validation means.

00:46:28.780 --> 00:46:31.780
It's like checking to see if the data is correct.

00:46:31.780 --> 00:46:35.780
And the way that you would do this, there's lots of different ways you could

00:46:35.780 --> 00:46:37.780
do this, lots of different technologies you could do this,

00:46:37.780 --> 00:46:40.780
but I'm going to just talk from a DataWorks point of view,

00:46:40.780 --> 00:46:47.780
which is that we advise our customers to basically build out like three sort

00:46:47.780 --> 00:46:52.780
of main layers of tables when you're building any kind of data pipeline

00:46:52.780 --> 00:46:54.780
or working on any kind of project.

00:46:54.780 --> 00:46:58.780
There's this concept of a bronze table.

00:46:58.780 --> 00:47:00.780
There's basically bronze, silver, and gold.

00:47:00.780 --> 00:47:05.780
So the idea is that bronze is data as you found it, like as it came to you.

00:47:05.780 --> 00:47:07.780
So you just capture it as you found it.

00:47:07.780 --> 00:47:08.780
You put it in the bronze table.

00:47:08.780 --> 00:47:10.780
It could be flawed, whatever.

00:47:10.780 --> 00:47:11.780
It doesn't matter.

00:47:11.780 --> 00:47:15.780
You want to get it exactly as you found it so you have a copy of the raw data

00:47:15.780 --> 00:47:16.780
as it is.

00:47:16.780 --> 00:47:21.780
Then you have some sort of code that you write that has logic to run all of the

00:47:21.780 --> 00:47:25.780
validation and check to make sure that you basically are, you know,

00:47:25.780 --> 00:47:29.780
filtering out rows that have incorrect dates, stuff like that, right?

00:47:29.780 --> 00:47:33.780
That's going to, and like dealing with missing values, things like that.

00:47:33.780 --> 00:47:37.780
Then you're going to have a set of silver tables that are complete

00:47:37.780 --> 00:47:42.780
observations, they're tidy data, and they've already been transformed.

00:47:42.780 --> 00:47:45.780
They've already had some sort of logic applied to it.

00:47:45.780 --> 00:47:51.780
At the third level, the gold tables are essentially aggregates of the silver

00:47:51.780 --> 00:47:52.780
tables.

00:47:52.780 --> 00:47:55.780
So if you have single observations, your gold tables are going to be, if you

00:47:55.780 --> 00:47:59.780
did a group by and you made some sort of aggregation, that would be your gold

00:47:59.780 --> 00:48:01.780
level tables.

00:48:01.780 --> 00:48:06.780
So in this way, you have a pretty clear, it's sort of like as you go further in

00:48:06.780 --> 00:48:10.780
the pipeline, you know, more and more business logic has been applied to it.

00:48:10.780 --> 00:48:15.780
You can always go back to the bronze table and see the source of where it came

00:48:15.780 --> 00:48:18.780
from, even if it was flawed.

00:48:18.780 --> 00:48:22.780
And then you also can see the logic that transformed it and made it clear.

00:48:22.780 --> 00:48:27.780
So that's what I think data validation means, a meaning of data validation.

00:48:27.780 --> 00:48:32.780
And that's how we would take care of it is essentially you have to write the

00:48:32.780 --> 00:48:36.780
code to clean it up, but you should stage the data in these different tables,

00:48:36.780 --> 00:48:43.780
these different layers so that it's very clear each step of the way.

00:48:43.780 --> 00:48:44.780
Okay.

00:48:44.780 --> 00:48:51.780
And, and if they asked about like consistency in the data, what do they exactly

00:48:51.780 --> 00:48:55.780
mean by consistent consistency in the data set?

00:48:55.780 --> 00:49:03.780
Like, for example, if I'm getting a data with a frequency of once a month, so

00:49:03.780 --> 00:49:10.780
how would I want to make sure that the data is consistent, like the tables, the

