00:50:30.780 --> 00:50:32.780
cluster after X minutes of inactivity.

00:50:32.780 --> 00:50:35.780
Like when you end up trying to launch the cluster, you're not allowed to do

00:50:35.780 --> 00:50:36.780
that.

00:50:36.780 --> 00:50:39.780
But if I do a regular R instance and then I use Databricks Notebook, I'm

00:50:39.780 --> 00:50:41.780
able to do that.

00:50:41.780 --> 00:50:47.780
I was wondering if there's any avenue forward to make that a feature

00:50:47.780 --> 00:50:50.780
available, or if there's a pipeline for that, or maybe I switched to

00:50:50.780 --> 00:50:54.780
Posit Workbench and maybe there's a solution there that I'm not aware of.

00:50:54.780 --> 00:50:55.780
Yeah.

00:50:55.780 --> 00:50:59.780
So just to make sure I got everything, you're using the hosted RStudio in

00:50:59.780 --> 00:51:00.780
Databricks?

00:51:00.780 --> 00:51:01.780
Yes.

00:51:01.780 --> 00:51:02.780
Yeah.

00:51:02.780 --> 00:51:03.780
Okay.

00:51:03.780 --> 00:51:07.780
So just for people who may not know on the call, Databricks does offer the

00:51:07.780 --> 00:51:15.780
ability to install RStudio on the driver node or on an instance that you

00:51:15.780 --> 00:51:17.780
launch on Databricks.

00:51:17.780 --> 00:51:21.780
So you can open it up in your web browser and you can start working with the

00:51:21.780 --> 00:51:23.780
data that's in Databricks.

00:51:23.780 --> 00:51:32.780
There's like some requirements though for you to do this, and they make it

00:51:32.780 --> 00:51:34.780
hard to work with.

00:51:34.780 --> 00:51:37.780
So one of the biggest ones is that Databricks clusters by, or compute by

00:51:37.780 --> 00:51:41.780
definition, like the default setting is that it'll turn off if you're not

00:51:41.780 --> 00:51:43.780
using it, which is great.

00:51:43.780 --> 00:51:48.780
But for this, if you want to launch RStudio, then we force you to disable the

00:51:48.780 --> 00:51:49.780
auto termination.

00:51:49.780 --> 00:51:50.780
So it will not turn off.

00:51:50.780 --> 00:51:52.780
You have to manually turn it off.

00:51:52.780 --> 00:51:55.780
So the reason why we do that is IDEs are stateful.

00:51:55.780 --> 00:52:01.780
You want to preserve the code that you've written and maybe some data that

00:52:01.780 --> 00:52:02.780
you've saved locally.

00:52:02.780 --> 00:52:06.780
So we don't want you to walk away from your computer for an hour and then we

00:52:06.780 --> 00:52:08.780
shut that down and you lost everything.

00:52:08.780 --> 00:52:14.780
So we make it so that you can't auto terminate it.

00:52:14.780 --> 00:52:19.780
So the ways to get around this, there's two ways.

00:52:19.780 --> 00:52:24.780
The best way is to not use this feature, to be honest with you.

00:52:24.780 --> 00:52:28.780
The better way to go is to use RStudio desktop or deposit workbench and then

00:52:28.780 --> 00:52:31.780
set up like a remote connection or to use Databricks notebooks inside of

00:52:31.780 --> 00:52:34.780
Databricks if you can't do that.

00:52:34.780 --> 00:52:40.780
However, if you want to work around, then there's a package out there called

00:52:40.780 --> 00:52:42.780
Brickster.

00:52:42.780 --> 00:52:45.780
I'm so glad I got a chance to bring this up.

00:52:45.780 --> 00:52:50.780
One second.

00:52:50.780 --> 00:52:52.780
We're going to write some blogs about this this year.

00:52:52.780 --> 00:52:57.780
But this is my colleague, Zach Davies, who's in Australia.

00:52:57.780 --> 00:53:03.780
But you can use the REST API, the Databricks REST API, to turn off and

00:53:03.780 --> 00:53:05.780
turn on clusters.

00:53:05.780 --> 00:53:08.780
So it's very easy to use Brickster, write some R code that basically

00:53:08.780 --> 00:53:12.780
identifies your cluster with RStudio on it and shuts it off.

00:53:12.780 --> 00:53:16.780
So what I've advised customers in the past is maybe at like 10 p.m.

00:53:16.780 --> 00:53:20.780
and you don't think people are going to be using it anymore, then you can

00:53:20.780 --> 00:53:24.780
schedule a Databricks job or you can run it locally on your machine if you

00:53:24.780 --> 00:53:26.780
want, like a cron job.

00:53:26.780 --> 00:53:30.780
And then it'll hit the REST API and it'll shut it off.

00:53:30.780 --> 00:53:32.780
And you come back the next morning, you turn it on yourself, and then

00:53:32.780 --> 00:53:35.780
you're good to go.

00:53:35.780 --> 00:53:38.780
Does that make sense?

00:53:38.780 --> 00:53:39.780
Yeah, that's perfect.

