00:54:31.780 --> 00:54:36.780
But a question that I always ask Rafi, and it's one of my favorite questions,

00:54:36.780 --> 00:54:42.780
is there a piece of career advice that you have either given to somebody or

00:54:42.780 --> 00:54:50.780
received along your career journey that you'd like to share with us?

00:54:50.780 --> 00:54:57.780
Yeah, sure.

00:54:57.780 --> 00:55:07.780
Okay, the one that comes to mind is that I would recommend feeling free to ask

00:55:07.780 --> 00:55:12.780
questions when you don't understand something because you really have nothing

00:55:12.780 --> 00:55:15.780
to lose, and I'll explain why.

00:55:15.780 --> 00:55:22.780
If you don't understand something and you don't ask a question, then you will

00:55:22.780 --> 00:55:25.780
not understand it because you're not going to get the answer.

00:55:25.780 --> 00:55:29.780
If you don't understand it and you ask the question and you get the answer,

00:55:29.780 --> 00:55:31.780
then fantastic.

00:55:31.780 --> 00:55:32.780
Now you understand that.

00:55:32.780 --> 00:55:36.780
Now you're that much more knowledgeable and that much more capable.

00:55:36.780 --> 00:55:43.780
If you ask the question and people deride you or basically give you any other

00:55:43.780 --> 00:55:46.780
response than answering the question, then you know that maybe you're not in

00:55:46.780 --> 00:55:49.780
the best situation, and that's also valuable information, and you should

00:55:49.780 --> 00:55:53.780
maybe look for a place where you are free to ask questions.

00:55:53.780 --> 00:55:56.780
So I think that that's a really powerful thing.

00:55:56.780 --> 00:55:57.780
People are often afraid.

00:55:57.780 --> 00:55:59.780
So why wouldn't someone ask your question?

00:55:59.780 --> 00:56:03.780
Because they're afraid to look stupid or they're afraid to look like they don't

00:56:03.780 --> 00:56:04.780
know everything.

00:56:04.780 --> 00:56:07.780
The truth is nobody knows everything.

00:56:07.780 --> 00:56:11.780
One of the best experiences that I had at Databricks was when I first met some

00:56:11.780 --> 00:56:14.780
of the engineers that I admire so much, and I was asking them about some things,

00:56:14.780 --> 00:56:17.780
about how Databricks works, and without missing a beat, he said,

00:56:17.780 --> 00:56:19.780
I don't know.

00:56:19.780 --> 00:56:23.780
And I was just like, that's amazing that that's the culture, that you are just

00:56:23.780 --> 00:56:25.780
not afraid to just be like, oh, I don't know.

00:56:25.780 --> 00:56:26.780
That's not my area.

00:56:26.780 --> 00:56:27.780
I don't know that.

00:56:27.780 --> 00:56:29.780
So I think that that's the advice that I would give.

00:56:29.780 --> 00:56:33.780
I think it's served me very well, and I think it would serve anyone well.

00:56:33.780 --> 00:56:34.780
